The paper deals with multi-agent systems and game theory, which are core topics in computer science. The use of a global utility function and the concept of equilibrium actions suggest that the paper belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The focus on multi-agent systems and the use of a distributed algorithm suggest that the paper also belongs to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. The use of beliefs and uncertainty suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of the term "optimal behavior" suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the use of algorithms and convergence analysis suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
